sentences: Fučík was born in Prague, Bohemia, on 18 July 1872 when Prague was part of the Austro-Hungarian Empire.
In 1891, he joined the 49th Austro-Hungarian Regiment as a military musician.
In 1894, he left the army to take up a position as second bassoonist at the German Theatre in Prague.
In 1897, he rejoined the army as the bandmaster for the 86th Infantry Regiment based in Sarajevo.
In 1910, Canadian composer Louis-Phillipe Laurendeau arranged "Entrance of the Gladiators" for a small band, under the title "Thunder and Blazes."
In 1900, Fučík's band was moved to Budapest where he found there were eight regimental bands ready to play his compositions, but he also faced more competition to get noticed.
In 1910, Fučík moved again, returning to Bohemia where he became the bandmaster of the 92nd Infantry Regiment in Theresienstadt.
In 1913, Fučík settled in Berlin where he started his own band, the Prager Tonkünstler-Orchester, and a music publishing company, Tempo Verlag, to market his compositions.
On 25 September 1916, Julius Fučík died in Berlin at the age of 44, likely of a heart attack.

sentences: Julius Ernest Wilhelm Fučík (Czech: [ˈjulɪjus ˈfutʃiːk]; 18 July 1872 – 25 September 1916) was a Czech composer and conductor of military bands.
Today his marches are still played as patriotic music in the Czech Republic.

His worldwide reputation rests primarily on two works: "The Florentiner March", popular throughout much of Europe, and the "Entrance of the Gladiators" (Vjezd gladiátorů), which is widely recognized, often under the title "Thunder and Blazes", as one of the most popular theme tunes for circus clowns.
A year later he became the conductor of the Danica Choir in the Croatian city of Sisak.
Originally titled Grande Marche Chromatique, his interest in Roman history led him to rename the march as he did.
This version of his most famous march has words:  Big Red Noses
